{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2549"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2549"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.04,0.24,0.59,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2549"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54213"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2549"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2549"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39689"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"474"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2658"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"9876"},{"type":"tags","id":"11539"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2596"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2601"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54213"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old woman presents due to constant headaches. There is no photophobia, lacrimation, nausea nor vomiting. There is no family history of hypertension or migraine. She does not take any medications or illicit drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 182/105 mmHg and pulse rate 90/min. Auscultation reveals normal heart sounds. An abdominal bruit can be heard over the upper right quadrant. Neurological examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory results reveal serum potassium 3.1 mmol/L (3.5-5.2) and serum bicarbonate 33 mmol/L (22-32). Serum creatinine is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dexamethasone suppression test","Echocardiography","Plasma metanephrines","Renal vascular imaging","Renal venous sampling"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has secondary hypertension due to renal artery stenosis (RAS). Secondary causes of hypertension are usually suspected in following situations:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENew-onset hypertension at age \u0026lt;30 years with negative family history of hypertension\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResistant hypertension (ie, persistent hypertension after use of \u22653 antihypertensive medications)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypertension associated with hypokalaemia and metabolic alkalosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u2019s age raises suspicion for secondary hypertension. Her abdominal examination revealing unilateral bruit is suggestive of renal artery stenosis on the right side. RAS leads to activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS). Activation of RAAS causes increased production of renin in the juxtaglomerular cells of the affected kidney. The elevated renin leads to increased production of aldosterone and subsequently causes systemic hypertension. Excess aldosterone production also leads to hypokalaemia and elevated serum bicarbonate. Serum creatinine may be elevated in bilateral disease. Unilateral disease may have normal creatinine since the unaffected kidney compensates. The most appropriate initial test for patients suspected of RAS is \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal vascular imaging \u003C/strong\u003E(eg, renal Doppler ultrasonography, CT/MR angiography). Conventional renal arteriography is recommended if initial noninvasive tests are inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDexamethasone suppression test\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended in patients with Cushing syndrome. Cushing syndrome is one of the causes of secondary hypertension. However, other clinical features (eg, easy bruisability, abdominal striae, hyperglycaemia, weight gain) are also seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E may be the most appropriate next step if this patient was suspected to have coarctation of the aorta. An abdominal bruit and abnormal electrolyte findings seen in this patient are unlikely to be seen in the coarctation of the aorta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma metanephrines\u003C/strong\u003E are recommended in patients with pheochromocytoma. Pheochromocytoma presents with episodes of headaches, hypertension, diaphoresis, and palpitations. An abdominal bruit and hypokalaemia are unlikely to be seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal venous sampling\u003C/strong\u003E can help with the diagnosis of RAS. However, it is not used commonly nowadays since more sensitive and noninvasive tests like Doppler ultrasonography are available. If renal venous sampling was performed in this patient, it would show increased renin in the right renal vein (due to increased activity of RAAS), decreased renin in the left renal vein, and increased aldosterone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Renal artery stenosis is an important cause of secondary hypertension in young adults."],"references":["Manaktala R, Tafur-Soto JD, White CJ. Renal Artery Stenosis in the Patient with Hypertension: Prevalence, Impact and Management. Integr Blood Press Control. 2020 Jun 2;13:71-82. doi: 10.2147/IBPC.S248579."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39689"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2549"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39689"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-01T15:43:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-01T15:44:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2549"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54213"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","syno